abeth and her supporters’ use of the Old Testament to provide justification for decisions (or the lack thereof), to offer counsel to the Queen, and to vindicate both female kingship and the royal supremacy. It argues that biblical analogies were a vital component of Elizabethan royal iconography, and that their widespread use demonstrates their potency as a tool for legitimizing and sustaining her power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aBible and politicszEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aDivine right of kings. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Tudor & Elizabethan Era (1485-1603).2bisacsh  aElizabeth I.  aOld Testament.  abiblical analogies.  aearly modern religion.  apolitics and religion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831110237480 cprintz978164189381740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781802700770?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781802700770423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781802700770/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK